                <fr:title text="Terminology surrounding polynomials">Terminology surrounding polynomials</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/lankham-2016-linear/" title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics" uri="http://localhost:8000/lankham-2016-linear/" display-uri="lankham-2016-linear" type="local">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Section 3.2</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}_{0}]]></fr:tex> be a non-negative integer. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0},…,a_{n}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> be complex numbers. Then we call the expression
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[p(z)=a_{n}z^{n}+…+a_{1}z+a_{0}]]></fr:tex>
a <html:dfn>Polynomial</html:dfn> in the variable <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex> with <html:dfn>Coefficients</html:dfn> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0}]]></fr:tex>, …, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n}]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\neq 0]]></fr:tex>, we call <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> the <html:dfn>Degree</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> usually writing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (p)=n]]></fr:tex>. We call <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n}]]></fr:tex> the <html:dfn>Leading Coefficient</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(z)]]></fr:tex>. When <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n}=1]]></fr:tex> we call <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(z)]]></fr:tex> <html:dfn>Monic</html:dfn>.</html:p>
                <html:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=a_{0}=0]]></fr:tex>, then we call <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p(z)=0]]></fr:tex> the <html:dfn>Zero Polynomial</html:dfn>. Convention dictates <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\deg (0)=-\infty ]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
                <html:p>We also call:</html:p>
                <html:ul><html:li>degree zero polnomials are called <html:dfn>constant polynomials</html:dfn></html:li>
<html:li>degree one polnomials are called <html:dfn>linear polynomials</html:dfn></html:li>
<html:li>degree two polnomials are called <html:dfn>quadratic polynomials</html:dfn></html:li>
<html:li>degree three polnomials are called <html:dfn>cubic polynomials</html:dfn></html:li>
<html:li>degree four polnomials are called <html:dfn>quartic polynomials</html:dfn></html:li>
<html:li>degree five polnomials are called <html:dfn>quintic polynomials</html:dfn></html:li>
<html:li>… and so on.</html:li></html:ul>
              </fr:mainmatter>
